Opinion

Firdaus

Dear Western Feminists

June 1st, 2017

By Firdaus

Egyptian prostitute, prisoner, student, and prisoner.

Every life writes a narrative. Mine is too busy to tell now; one cannot fully comprehend the details in an article. It would require a novel. Yet today, I, soon to exit this earth, bearing the scalding brands of subjugation and exploitation, stand before you to share a plea.

My defiance took root in a childhood steeped in gender-based violence, navigating a harsh, rural, landscape. Like many other Egyptian women, flesh was cut from between my thighs, not only my genitals mutilated, but my self violated. This tradition continues.

In the underbelly of society, as a prostitute, I discovered a twisted autonomy. The grimy offers from men became transactional devices, affording me a certain power, seemingly an unsettling emancipation. Yet, I was cornered into this life due to a capitalist structure that punished my gender, positioning me as a commodity. Ironically, my so-called 'reputable' office work came with its own chains, confining me to the margins of society and blocking paths of upward mobility, often worse than prostitution.

Here, I ask, where is the Western feminist critique of this capitalistic model that thrives on marking out 'respectable' realms of work? In a struggle for my own personal freedoms, I realized the void of your understanding. You urge the necessity of recognizing these deep-seated oppressive traditions within your discourse for equality. Yet, you exist within this system, and rather than moving beyond it, you simply accept it.

I ask your attention, for the attention lives navigated of women like myself. In primary school, I connected with a beloved female teacher, although she remained at arm's length. My alliance with a brothel-madam was layered with complexity, and my liberation from an abuser came from the kindness of a female neighbor—each revealing the diverse dimensions of gendered relationships. This is a good metaphor for your feminism: relationships that may seem to resist, yet only put a bandage on a larger flesh wound. Your feminism, as I see it, ought to mature from a monolithic perception of sisterhood, embracing and vocalizing the core problems, the issues that women of varied cultures experience, rather than just your own.

Sign up for the Egypt Briefing.  The latest news about the Middle East.

Your feminism often discards cultural norms. My critique of Arab men and patriarchal conventions – which lead to the life I head today – was born from a life buried under their weight. Yet, the this oppression and its opposing strategies of resistance are deep-seated in cultural frameworks. The west falls into the trap of a unilateral, over-generalized approach to solving the issues of women. Your discourse lacks respect for any plurality; an acceptance of multiple routes of resistance.

Lastly, to speak on radical defiance. My killing of a man, a pimp, an abuser, an embodiment of the forces I faced, the forces Arab women face on the daily: it was resistance. But it was also a culmination of my life experience. Western feminism's narratives often label women like me as passive victims, while simultaneously engaging in conscience free "protest." I will die for what I did. Yet my story is dismissed in favor of "marches on Washington," the pink hats a parody of what protest actually means: self-sacrifice.

So I ask this – what is the goal of feminism in the west. Is it truly for liberation? If so, then it has a heavy task ahead: It must learn to read stories far removed from its context; those like mine and countless others. It must absorb our struggles, resistances, and victories. True feminist discourse should adopt inclusivity, thrive on intersection, and empower all women, irrespective of their origins.

So here I sit, rotting away, in a prison for a crime society committed. I have spent my life gaining victories in shadowed corners that a your discourse often overlooks. Feminism should not solely ride on the waves of Western norms, but the struggles of womanhood itself. Until you accomplish this, you do not fight for women; only those who benefit from the oppression exerted by men themselves.

Firdaus, once an indigent Egyptian woman who endured insurmountable trials in her life due to societal norms and gender inequality, was executed as an egyptian death row inmate. Her life story, being a journey from destitution to self-assertiveness and independence, continues to inspire and influence dialogues on gender and social reform around the world
